abstract: The Republicans of the Fifteenth Assembly District met yesterday in Krom's Hall, No. 246 West Thirty-third-street, for the election of officers and delegates to the Central Committee. Mr. HENRY D. LAPAUGH presided, and was assisted by Messrs. Simpson, Stewart, Hopper, Julich, Wilder and Turner. The utmost good feeling prevailed, and at the close of the proceedings a warm veto of thanks was passed to Mr. LEPAUGH for his services to the Republican Party.

abstract: Last year, by direction of the Brooklyn Street Commissioners, Butler-street, from Fourth to Flatbush-avenue, at great cost, was paved with the Belgian patent. abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 4 1 P.M. The barometer has fallen since Thursday on the California coast, and remained stationary from the Rock Mountains to the upper lakes. It has fallen from the Mississippi to the Atlantic. The area of lowest barometer has extended from the lower lakes eastward over New-England, and that of highest barometer remains over Louisiana and Texas.

abstract: The arrangements are nearly completed for holding a public demonstration in this City Tuesday next, that being the one hundredth anniversary of Sir WALTER SCOTT'S birthday. abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 8--1 A.M.--The barometer has fallen since Sunday night in the Upper Mississippi Valley, and the area of the lowest pressure now extends from Lake Ontario to Nebraska and northward. Rain has fallen an the Gulf Coast, and coast rains in the South Atlantic States.

abstract: CHICAGO, Aug. 12. Senator SCHURZ, who had been induced by a large number of Germans in this city to give them his views on political topics, addressed a large audience in Farwell Hall, this evening, in German. abstract: The arrangements for the WALTER SCOTT centennial anniversary, to be held in this City on Tuesday next, by the Scotch residents, are now fully completed. In the morning the various Scotch societies of Brooklyn, New-York, and Hudson County will meet at the head-quarters of the New-York Caledonian Club, on Sulliavan-street, and will subsequently parade through Houstonstreet, Broadway to Twenty-third-street, and Fifth-avenue to Thirty-second-street and Fourth-avenue, where they will take cars for Central Park.

abstract: The German Government, as well as the Berlin authorities, have adopted the most stringent measures for the prevention of the spread of the cholera. Twenty-three persons were attacked with the disease at Konigsberg on Friday, thirteen of whom are already dead. No cases of cholera have appeared in the South of Russia.

abstract: D.W. SOUTER, the United States Express delivery messenger, whose wagon was robbed recently, and who is under arrest for being implicated in the robbery, confesses he was concerned in it. He tells different stories about being urged to assist in the robbery of the Company, that he resisted, but finally yielded and entered into the robbery with J. SCANON and THOMAS GRADY, who are also under arrest. KENDALL, the driver, knew nothing of the affair.

abstract: On Saturday afternoon a novel exhibition was given at the State Fair grounds at Waverly. N.J., which was attended by a large assemblage of gentlemen interested in transportation, mechanics and mining. The occasion was the first public trial in America of the traction engines, manufactured in England, which were rendered so serviceable by the German Army during the late war in the transportation of supplies over country roads.

abstract: The monthly concert of the Morning Star Sunday-school, at No. 130 West Twenty-fourthstreet, yesterday afternoon, was as entertaining as usual. There was a fine attendance of children and grown folks despite the season, which has, no doubt, taken many of the habitues to the sea-side and rural retreats. Some colored children were present likewise. The exercises were opened with singing, Scripture reading, conducted by Dr. R.P. PERRY, and prayer by Rev. G.W. HEACOCK, of Buffalo.

The facts as they were then known were told in full in the TIMES of yesterday, but they showed only that a man with his skull crushed had been found at the place stated, about 1 o'clock Saturday morning; that he had died while being taken to the Station-house, and that all efforts then made to discover the identity of the dead man, or the manner in which he came to his death, had proved fruitless. DYER PANGBURN, of East Frankfort, Herkimer County, beat his wife to death about midnight of Monday and then hung himself in his barn. Information of the terrible affair was first given by the children of Mrs. PANGBURN, who went to the house of Mr. WALBY, a neighbor, about 5 o'clock Tuesday morning, and, having awakened his wife, told her that their mother had been killed by PANGBURN during the night. abstract: JAMES HOGAN, an engineer on the Erie Railway, was instantly killed last night a Hohokus, on the Eastern Division, under singular circumstances. abstract: For the purpose of bringing together the American and Canadian yachts and yachtsmen of the Lakes, a number of gentlemen of Detroit, Toledo, Sandusky, Cleveland, and other places on Lake Erie have arranged to hold a grand regatta at Put-in-Bay on the 6th and 7th of September next. The idea has found much favor in Canadian yachting circles, and should prove a success.

abstract: PARIS, Aug. 25.--In the Assembly, today, the amended bill providing for the gradual disbandment of the National Guard was passed. The journals sorrowfully comment on the scenes in the Assembly yesterday. It is said that M. THIERS will accept no compromise on the question of the prolongation of his powers. Gen. FAIDHERBE has written a letter censuring the Assembly and resigning his seat as a Deputy.

abstract: Official returns of all but one county in Kentucky, received in Frankfort, give the following result: Harlan, 89,578; Leslie, 126,059. The other country, Wolfe, is unofficially reported to have given 216 votes for Harlan and 388 for Leslie, making the total vote of the State: Harlan, 89,224; Leslie, 126,447; Leslie's majority, 37,153. The complete official vote may vary slightly from this.

abstract: The funeral rites over the late WILLIAM IRVING GRAHAM, who died on the 26th inst. were solemnized yesterday afternoon, at Trinity Chapel. Rev. Dr. VINTON and Dr. HODGES officiated. Twelve members of the Society of the Cincinnati, of which deceased was for many years a prominent member, acted as pall-bearers. A number of others connected with that Society followed the remains from his late residence to Trinity Cemetery, the place of interment.
